      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2dfce99dc6016689",
      "text": "There’s been a lot of buzz around using mobile devices as the [[Second screen]] for watching TV shows and using other desktop or web page-based applications.\n\nI’ve tried this out in a few different formats with varying success/interest, but I’m convinced that a mobile app second screen is exactly what federated wiki needs.  There are two reasons why I believe this: 1) News Feeds and 2) Feedback\n\nOn Newsfeeds:\n\nI use the Feedly app on my phone to catch up on news/RSS feeds when I’m standing in line or otherwise have a few seconds to kill.  If something resonates with me, I’ll make a quick note in Evernote or jot it on a napkin if I happen to have a pen with me.  Then I’ll follow up on that thought (by emailing someone, tweeting, writing a paper, making a blog post, drawing on my whiteboard -- whatever) when I get back to my office.\n\nIn FedWiki, I’ve been grabbing my laptop, clicking “Happening Folks”, clicking “Recent Changes”, and watching the icons spin while the latest stories filter in.  Ideally, I’d love to be able to pick up my phone and see this feed immediately – maybe even see a preview of how many items changed in the last hour (or some other interval) via the little red number on the app icon (ASIDE:  I feel like I should know what that number is called).  Maybe we can export a version of the JSON for that page into an XML RSS format so I can see it in Feedly?  Maybe we can write an iOS app that shows updates?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ea4259bf6edde2cf",
      "text": "[[BillSeitz]] notes that if you put a [[Recent Changes]] link at the bottom of your [[Happening Folks]] page then you can follow that series of clicks (from Welcome to Folks to Recent) and end up with a URL you can bookmark and jump right to."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9805d1764939df98",
      "text": "On Feedback:\n\nI really like this FedWiki happening.  I really like a lot of the articles and a lot if the comments.   I realize that I’m about to make a lame-sounding statement, and at the risk of sounding like a Facebook fanatic:  There have been many times that I really wished there was a Like button.  \n\nI realize that this goes against many of the FedWiki collaborative tenets (such as [[Dissertation over Discourse]], as well as ideas about forming the community dynamically, which are presented in [[we make the road by walking]]), so that’s where the App comes in.  Maybe the web interface doesn’t show likes, but the App does.  Also, the likes could be used behind the scenes to help decide which posts appear in your feed (based on posts you’ve liked in the past).\n\nAdditionally, it would be great to get a notification when someone forks or comments on one of my posts.  Keeping these out of the web interface but putting them in an App may be a way to maintain those FedWiki tenets while still offering notifications for those who want them."
